Data Mining

Code, modify and maintain SQL scripts to perform data pulling tasks

  • SELECT statement (also nested select statement)
  • Table JOIN
  • WHERE clause
  • UNION operator
  • GROUP BY statement
  • HAVING clause
  • ORDER BY keyword

SQL example:

SELECT DISTINCT 
          ***,
              (select X.***   
          from(
          select ***
          from ***
          ) X)      as ***
FROM **                 A    
LEFT JOIN **            B  ON A.***             = B.***
WHERE A.**** >= **
       
UNION
     
SELECT DISTINCT 
          ***,
              null
FROM **                 C    
JOIN **                 D  ON C.***             = D.***
WHERE A.**** < **
       
GROUP BY ***
HAVING *** not in (22, 33)
ORDER BY ***
;

Create and call SQL function when performing complicated pulls

Example: want to add a column that matches person with their countries separated by comma:

Person_Name Country_Name
AAA, BBB, CCC China, US, Canada

SQL function call in query:

  select P.Person_Name,
           get_all_countries(P.Person_Name)
    from person P
    ;

SQL function:

create or replace FUNCTION   get_all_countries
             (person_name_in person.person_name%TYPE)

    CURSOR COUNTRY_CUR IS
    SQL script here
    ;

-- ---------------------------

COUNTRY_CD                country.country_cd%type;
CONCATE_COUNTRY_CD                  LONG := '';

BEGIN
   OPEN COUNTRY_CUR;
   LOOP
    FETCH COUNTRY_CUR INTO COUNTRY_CD;
    EXIT WHEN COUNTRY_CUR%NOTFOUND;

  IF  CONCATE_COUNTRY_CD is null THEN
       CONCATE_COUNTRY_CD := COUNTRY_CD ;
       ELSE
      CONCATE_COUNTRY_CD := CONCATE_COUNTRY_CD||'; '||COUNTRY_CD;
    END IF;

   END LOOP;


   CLOSE COUNTRY_CUR;

RETURN CONCATE_COUNTRY_CD;
--
EXCEPTION
    WHEN OTHERS THEN
        CLOSE COUNTRY_CUR;
        RAISE;
END;
-- END PL/SQL BLOCK (do not remove this line) --------------------

Data summarization:

  • select()
  • filter()
  • mutate()
  • group_by()
  • arrange()
  • count()
  • summarise()
a_paid <- df %>%
  mutate(YEAR = internal_function(fs_year,indicator = "-")) %>%
  left_join(df2, by=c("col1_p_cd"="col2_p_cd")) %>%
  left_join(distinct(df3,
                   same_name_col,
                   COL_FIELD) %>%
  mutate(AMOUNT = rowSums(.[grepl("PAYMENT_AMT", names(.))])) %>%
  group_by(COL) %>%
    summarise(TOTAL = sum(AMOUNT),
              .groups = "drop") %>%
    ungroup() %>%
    filter(TOTAL > 1)

Plot implementation:

u15_with_non_15_plot <- ggplot(dframe, 
                               aes(x = YEAR, y = SIZE, color = INSTITUTION, group=INSTITUTION)) +
                                geom_line() + 
                                labs(x = "Fiscal Year", y = "Average Grant Size") +
                                ggtitle("U15 vs Non-U15") +
                                scale_colour_discrete(name = "Institution Type") +
                                scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::unit_format(unit = "k", scale = 1e-3))
  
# u15_with_non_15_plot

ggsave("u15_with_non_15_plot.png", u15_with_non_15_plot, width = 8, height = 5)

Data export:

wb <- internal_function(...)

money_fmt <- createStyle(numFmt = 'CURRENCY')

addWorksheet(wb, "Output")
setColWidths(wb, "Output", cols = 1:ncol(result_print),
             widths = c(10, 50, 23, 23, 20, 35, 28))

# write data  
writeDataTable(wb, "Output", 
               result_print)

#style header
addStyle(wb, "Output", 
         style = internal_style,
         rows = 1, cols = 1:ncol(result_print), 
         gridExpand = TRUE, stack = TRUE)

# style money
addStyle(wb, "Output",
         style = money_fmt,
         rows = 2:(nrow(result_print) + 1),
         cols = 6:7,
         gridExpand = TRUE, stack = TRUE)

# save workbook
saveWorkbook(wb, here::here("folder",
                            sprintf("%s.xlsx", fs::path_sanitize("title"))),
             overwrite = TRUE)

Other R Libraries

Diffr to Compare Two .sql Files

## load libraries
library(diffr)
## Warning: package 'diffr' was built under R version 4.0.3
## first move two files we want to compare under utility_dir path.
## replace sample file names with ones we want to compare
old <- "img/Sample_1.sql"
new <- "img/Sample_2.sql"
## run following code, differences will appear in the console
diffr(old, new)

Arsenal to Compare Excel Spreadsheets

library(arsenal)
## Warning: package 'arsenal' was built under R version 4.0.3
library(readxl)
## Warning: package 'readxl' was built under R version 4.0.3
library(dplyr)


### read two excel spreadsheets

old <- read_excel("img/Sample_1.xlsx")

new <- read_excel("img/Sample_2.xlsx")

# order data in two df in same way
old <- old %>%
  arrange(YEAR,
          NAME,
          DATE)
new <- new %>%
  arrange(YEAR,
          NAME,
          DATE)

## this code will print comparison result to console. 
comparedf(old, new)
